cmes.note: Narrow, diffuse CME first seen to the East in SOHO LASCO C2 beginning at 2025-09-21T02:48Z, as well as faintly by STEREO A COR2 in later frames. This CME is only visible for a few frames in STEREO A COR2 due to a reduced, 1-hour cadence, and is not visible in SOHO LASCO C3 or GOES CCOR-1 due to faintness. There is no clear source seen for this event.

cmeAnalyses.note: Plane-of-sky measurement due to uncertain source location and lack of available coronagraph imagery to triangulate.

cmes.note: Narrow, very faint, jet-like CME seen SSE in all 3 coronagraphs (SOHO LASCO, STEREO A COR2 and GOES CCOR-1) but only for a few timestamps, after which it becomes too faint. Its front is fuzzy and not clear in all timestamps. No clear source has been found for this event.

cmeAnalyses.note: A very uncertain analysis based on the fit with all three coronagraphs (SOHO LASCO, STEREO A COR2 and GOES CCOR-1). No source has been found for this CME in available EUV imagery to confirm this analysis.

cmes.note: Faint loop CME seen to the NW in SOHO LASCO (and possibly to the N in STEREO A COR2 in one timestamp before data gap). It is likely completely covered by a data gap in STEREO A and is covered by the pylon in GOES CCOR-1. It is better seen in running difference imagery. Its source is a large loop-like prominence that gradually develops on/behind the NW limb as seen from GOES SUVI starting after 2025-09-21T19Z (in GOES SUVI 304). The filament eruption is also seen close to the NW limb in STEREO A EUVI 304 and 195 around (N30W70, very approximately).

cmeAnalyses.note: Updated measurement including STEREO A COR2A imagery.
Speculative analysis with one coronagraph (SOHO LASCO), based on the very approximate source location (as seen in STEREO A EUVI close to the NW limb).

cmes.note: Faint asymmetrical CME with an irregular front to the NE with the start time that could be even earlier. The CME overlaps with a NE streamer making analysis more difficult. Source is likely a large prominence eruption seen in GOES SUVI 304 and STEREO A EUV 304, slowly developing close to the NE limb (very approx. ~N50E70) after 2025-09-21T19Z and having two distinct lobes, with the more eastern lobe possibly falling back into corona.

cmeAnalyses.note: Very approximate  Analysis based on the fit with all three coronagraphs (SOHO LASCO, STEREO A COR2 and GOES CCOR-1). There seems to be a bit of a westward deflection from the source location.

cmes.note: A relatively bright jet-like CME seen to the ESE in SOHO LASCO and GOES CCOR-1 coronagraph and covered by the data gap in STEREO A COR2. No clear source has been found, however there is some activity on the E limb as seen in GOES SUVI 304.

cmeAnalyses.note: The CME is covered by a data gap in STEREO A COR2, so only LASCO and GOES CCOR-1 imagery is available for it. No clear source has been found for this event. Only plane-of-sky analysis is possible.

cmes.note:
Bright light-bulb shaped CME to the SW in SOHO LASCO, with the start covered by the data gap in STEREO A COR2 (the gap starts right before the CME start).
The source is a large prominence from behind the SW limb in GOES SUVI 304 and in the SW quadrant, not far from the SW limb in STEREO A EUV 304 and 195. The filament is centered around (S35W50) as seen from STEREO A, so around (S35W97) as we would see from Earth.

cmeAnalyses.note: Updated measurement with additional imagery.

cmes.note: This CME has a diffuse, faint leading edge but is visible to the east in SOHO LASCO C2, GOES CCOR-1, and STEREO A COR2 imagery. It is not observed in SOHO LASCO C3 imagery as it is blocked by the pylon. The source is likely related to an opening of field lines observed over the eastern limb starting around 2025-09-22T06:30Z as seen in GOES SUVI 171, 195, 284 imagery. Additionally, there is minor brightening centered near S05E45 which may be related to the opening of field lines.

cmeAnalyses.note: Measurement based on the best fit between SOHO LASCO C2, GOES CCOR-1, and STEREO A COR2 imagery.

cmes.note: This CME is visible to the southwest in SOHO LASCO C2/C3, GOES CCOR-1, and STEREO A COR2 imagery. The source is likely far-sided as there are no source signatures visible on the Earth-facing disk around the time of this event.

cmeAnalyses.note: Measurement based on the best fit between SOHO LASCO C3, GOES CCOR-1, and STEREO A COR2 imagery. As the source is likely far-sided, a precise source location is unknown. The measured parameters may vary slightly as a result.

cmes.note: CME observed to the NE in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and GOES CCOR-1, not observed in STEREO A COR2 due to a data gap. The source is a filament eruption observed near the NE limb which begins to lift off around 2025-09-22T14:30Z seen in GOES SUVI 171/195/304, which appears likely far-sided by the lack of on-disk brightening underneath the eruption. Post-eruptive arcade loops are faintly seen over the limb following the eruption, as well as by Solar Orbiter EUI 304 located at approx. N25E105.

cmeAnalyses.note: SOHO LASCO C3 only plane-of-sky as the CME front is more uniform by C3 FOV, and no STEREO A COR2 is available to triangulate how far-sided this source longitude is. Longitude fits range from approx. E125 and E80.

cmes.note: Bright loop CME first seen to the NW in SOHO LASCO C2 beginning 2025-09-22T21:36Z, as well as by SOHO LASCO C3, STEREO A COR2 and GOES CCOR-1. The source is rising field clearly over the far-sided NW limb, slowly starting ~18Z, more prominently visible starting 2025-09-22T20:35Z in SUVI 284.

cmeAnalyses.note: Measurement based on approximate source location and best fit in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and COR2A.

cmes.note: CME first seen in the SW by SOHO LASCO C2 beginning at 2025-09-23T00:12Z, as well as by SOHO LASCO C3, STEREO A COR2 and GOES CCOR-1 in later frames. The source of this event is a filament eruption seen beginning at approx. 2025-09-22T22:40Z from beyond the SW limb in GOES SUVI 304, and along the SW limb in STEREO A EUVI 304. Field line opening can also be seen in GOES SUVI 195.

cmeAnalyses.note: Measurement based on approximate source location and best fit between SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2. There is no GOES CCOR-1 imagery for this event due to an eclipse.

cmes.note: Faint CME observed to the SE in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and GOES CCOR-1. Not observed in STEREO A COR2 due to a data gap. No observable source is seen in GOES SUVI or STEREO A EUVI imagery.

cmeAnalyses.note: Plane-of-sky with SOHO LASCO C2/C3 as STEREO A COR2 not available due to a data gap and no eruption source is observed. CME is less than 10 HW.

cmes.note: Thin CME observed to the SW in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and GOES CCOR-1. This CME is not observed in STEREO A COR2, but it is a thin CME pointed almost directly at STEREO A (~W47.8 at this time) so it may be obscured by the occulting disk. The source may be a small brightening around S15W52 near AR 14217 beginning around 2025-09-23T22:52Z in GOES SUVI 171/195, with some field line movement extending over the SW limb at this time.

cmeAnalyses.note: Single spacecraft 3D measurement with SOHO LASCO C2/C3 only due to no visibility in STEREO A COR2, using the observed source near S15W52 as the basis and finding a good fit at these parameters.

cmes.note: This CME is visible to the southwest in SOHO LASCO C2/C3, STEREO A COR2, and GOES CCOR-1 coronagraphs. The source is obscured by an eclipse in GOES SUVI imagery, but there is minor brightening observed around 2025-09-24T04:15Z from Active Region 14217 (S16W50) in STEREO A EUVI 304 imagery. However, it is also possible this event is far-sided due to the uncertainty in the observed source.

cmeAnalyses.note: Measurement based on the best fit between SOHO LASCO C2 and STEREO A COR2 imagery. Due to uncertainty in the source location, the measured parameters may vary slightly.

cmes.note: This CME is visible to the southwest in SOHO LASCOC2/C3, GOES CCOR-1, and STEREO A COR2 imagery. The source may be related to an eruption from Active Region 14217 (S16W51) starting around 2025-09-24T05:50Z as seen in GOES SUVI 131, 171, 195, 304 imagery. However, there is faint field line movement visible over the southwest limb in GOES SUVI 284 imagery around this time which may also indicate a far-sided source.

cmeAnalyses.note: Measurement based on the best fit between SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2 imagery. The measured parameters may vary slightly due to uncertainty in the source location.

cmes.note: Jet CME seen to the SW in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and GOES CCOR-1. Seen extremely faintly in STEREO A COR2. Source is likely narrow opening field lines and an M1.0 flare seen from AR 14224 (S13W45) seen in GOES SUVI 195 starting around 2025-09-24T08:44Z. A small amount of ejecta can also be seen in STEREO A EUVI 304 at 2025-09-24T09:15Z.

cmeAnalyses.note: Best fit measurement using candidate source location, two frames of SOHO LASCO C2, and one frame STEREO A COR2. There is some uncertainty with this measurement due to the faintness of the leading edge and a data gap in SOHO LASCO lasting from 2025-09-24T09:24Z to 2025-09-24T12:00Z.

cmes.note: This CME is visible to the northeast in SOHO LASCO C2/C3, GOES CCOR-1, and STEREO A COR2 coronagraphs. The source is an eruption observed from beyond the northeast limb starting around 2025-09-24T10:40Z as seen in GOES SUVI 131, 171, 195, 284, 304 imagery.

cmeAnalyses.note: Measurement based on the approximate source location and best fit between SOHO LASCO C2 and STEREO A COR2 imagery.

cmes.note: This CME is visible to the southwest in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and GOES CCOR-1 imagery. It is currently not observed in STEREO A COR2 imagery due to a data gap starting at 2025-09-24T14:53Z. The source is likely related to an eruption from Active Region 14217 (S16W57) starting around 2025-09-24T14:00Z as seen in GOES SUVI 131, 171, 195, 304 imagery.

cmeAnalyses.note: Measured longitude based on the source location. The measured parameters may vary slightly due to a data gap in STEREO A COR2 imagery at the time of this event, preventing a stereoscopic measurement from being made.

cmes.note: Extremely narrow and faint jet seen to the SE in SOHO LASCO C2 and STEREO A COR2. No source has been found.

cmeAnalyses.note: Approximate analysis based on the fit with two coronagraphs (SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2). No source has been found for this CME in available EUV imagery.

cmes.note: Faint jet to the SW in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and GOES CCOR-1 and not seen in STEREO A COR2 coronagraph. One possible source could be AR 4217 (S17W65 at the time), marked by a minor brightening in this AR.

cmeAnalyses.note: Since the CME is not seen in STEREO A coronagraph and the source is not clear only plane-of-sky measurement is definitive.

cmes.note: Narrow fast jet with flattened front seen to the SW in SOHO LASCO C2/C3, GOES CCOR-1 and STEREO A COR2. Resembles 2025-09-24T14:36Z CME |  Source is likely a minor narrow filament eruption seen close to the SW limb in GOES SUVI 304 and (as brightening to the W of AR 14224 (this AR at the time was located at ~S13W54 as seen from L1)) in STEREO A EUV 304 around 2025-09-25T07:15Z.

cmeAnalyses.note: Analysis based on the fit with two coronagraphs and confirmed by the source seen in GOES SUVI and STEREO A EUV imagery near S17W75Z. Note that GOES CCOR-1 was not producing a good fit.

cmes.note: Narrow faint jet to the SW in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and GOES CCOR-1 and S in STEREO A COR2. No clear source has been found, however there is continuous activity near ARs 14217 and 14224 on 2025-09-25.

cmeAnalyses.note: Somewhat speculative analysis based on the fit with all three coronagraphs (SOHO LASCO, STEREO A COR2 and GOES CCOR-1), however since the CME is very faint and no clear source has been found for it we have no certainty that the narrow faint jet front we see S in STEREO A COR2 is the same jet we see SW in two other coronagraphs.

cmes.note: Narrow and faint CME seen to the NNE in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and GOES CCOR-1. Leading edge is not discernable in STEREO A COR2 imagery. Source is uncertain, but may be a tiny area of brightening seen in GOES SUVI 304 at 2025-09-25T13:57Z located at N49E70.

cmeAnalyses.note: Plane-of-sky measurement using SOHO LASCO C3 imagery.

cmes.note: Narrow CME seen to the NNE in SOHO LASCO C2/C3, STEREO A COR2, and GOES CCOR-1. Source is uncertain; there is no clear source in available UV imagery of the disk.

cmeAnalyses.note: Best fit measurement using several frames of SOHO LASCO C3 and STEREO A COR2.

cmes.note: Faint CME seen to the SW in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and GOES CCOR-1; extremely faint and seen to the SE in STEREO A COR2. Source is likely very minor dimming seen in STEREO A EUVI 195 starting around 2025-09-25T18:25Z, spanning from S20 to S40 and from about W38 to W58 (centered at S30W48).

cmeAnalyses.note: Best fit measurement using source location seen in UV imagery with some southeastward deflection, several frames of SOHO LASCO C2, one frame of SOHO LASCO C3, and one frame of STEREO A COR2. Leading edge becomes too diffuse to track a few frames into the SOHO LASCO C3 field of view.

cmes.note: Narrow jet CME to the ESE in all three coronagraphs (SOHO LASCO C2/C3, STEREO A COR2 and GOES CCOR-1). The source is likely a C3.6 flare from AR 14232 (N02E76) peaking at 2025-09-27T02:40Z.

cmeAnalyses.note: Analysis based on the fit of this narrow jet with SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2 and in alignment with the possible source - a C class flare from AR14232. No good fit with this analysis for CCOR-1.

cmes.note: A super faint narrow jet seen to the SE in SOHO LASCO C2 and STEREO A COR2 but not seen in C3 and GOES CCOR-1. Its source may be a narrow minor filament eruption in AR 14232 starting around 2025-09-27T03:20 as seen in GOES SUVI 304.

cmeAnalyses.note: Analysis based on the fit with SOHO LASCO C2 and STEREO A COR2 coronagraphs, confirming AR 14232 as a likely source.

cmes.note: A very faint narrow jet to the SE in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2. No clear source found but there is minor sparks in AR 14232 at the time.

cmeAnalyses.note: Corrected analysis based on the fit with two coronagraphs (SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2).
Approximate analysis based on the fit with two coronagraphs (SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2). Source is not clear but fit indicates that the culprit is likely AR 14232.

cmes.note: A faint CME to the SE in all three coronagraphs, possibly with a preceding fainter shock. Its source is the M1.1 flare from newly numbered AR 14232 (N02E74) and the associated wide fan-like filament eruption seen in GOES SUVI 304 starting at 2025-09-27T07:16Z, clearly directed southward of the AR. There seem to be two lobes to this event (an earlier southern lobe - the one seen clearer in COR2 coronagraph - and the northern, later lobe, best seen in CCOR-1 and not seen in COR2). The associated filament is also seen erupting on/behind the E limb as seen in STEREO A EUV 304 imagery at the time.

cmeAnalyses.note: Analysis including both the southern and the northern lobe of this CME and based on a fit with two coronagraphs (SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2). GOES CCOR-1 coronagraph (specifically the northern lobe of this CME as seen from CCOR-1) does not fit with this analysis.

cmes.note: Extremely faint narrow jet to the SE in SOHO LASCO C2 and STEREO A COR2, too faint to be seen in C3 and GOES CCOR-1. No source has been found.

cmeAnalyses.note: Approximate analysis based on the fit with SOHO LASCO C2 and STEREO A COR2 coronagraphs.  No source has been found for this CME.

cmes.note: Faint narrow CME to the NW visible in SOHO LASCO C2 and C3 imagery. The source appears to be a filament eruption along the NW limb starting around 2025-09-27T15:30Z in GOES SUVI 304.

cmeAnalyses.note: Plane of sky parameters based on best fit using SOHO LASCO C2/C3 imagery.

cmes.note: Seemingly two jet like CMEs treated as one in this as they are associated with the same source and traveling at similar speeds to the SE in SOHO LASCO C2, C3, GOES CCOR-1, and STEREO A COR2 imagery. The source is a C7.6 flare and associated filament ejecta visible in GOES SUVI 131, 304, and 284.

cmeAnalyses.note: Parameters based on best fit using SOHO LASCO C3 and STEREO A COR2 imagery.

cmes.note: Faint, slow CME visible to the NE as seen in SOHO LASCO C2. The source appears to be a slow filament eruption visible to the NE in GOES SUVI 304 starting around 2025-09-27T18:40Z along the NE limb.

cmeAnalyses.note: Plane of sky measurement using SOHO LASCO C2.

cmes.note: Somewhat asymmetrical CME directed eastward in all 3 coronagraphs (SOHO LASCO C2/C3, STEREO A COR2 and GOES CCOR-1). It has a clear follow-up front, best seen in CCOR-1. Its source is likely the impulsive M6.4 flare from AR 14232 (N03E59) seen in GOES-Secondary X-ray flux timeline (eclipsed in GOES-Primary) and with the associated significant fan-like filament/prominence eruption seen off/behind the SE limb in STEREO A EUV 304 and close to the limb in GOES SUVI 304 starting at 2025-09-28T08:45Z. There is also a minor brightening and a very minor opening of field lines near the E limb in GOES SUVI 195.

cmeAnalyses.note: Later analysis based on a good fit with two coronagraphs (SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2), also fitting GOES CCOR-1. This analysis is confirmed by the location of the CME source (M class flare from AR 14232), however there seems to be some eastward deflection from the location of this Active Region, based on the fit with coronagraphs.

Very preliminary analysis based on the location of the flare, with no SOHO LASCO C3 imagery yet and with an imperfect fit with GOES CCOR-1 and STEREO A COR2 coronagraphs. Needs to be reanalyzed once more LASCO imagery becomes available.

flares.note: Data gap in GOES-P (GOES-18) due to eclipse season.

Occulted flare from behind the NE limb, possibly from what would be later numbered as AR 14233. There is a very faint CME associated with this flare, only seen in several timestamps of SOHO LASCO C2 coronagraph and not seen in any other coronagraph. The speed of the CME is very low, under 200 km/s, so the CME has not been added to this database.
Impulsive flare covered by eclipse in GOES Primary.
